ا; Alif; ox head. Strength / Leader.
ب; Ba; house. House / Dwelling.
ت; Ta; mark. Mark / Covenant.
ث; Tha; dotted Ta. Make Manifest / Bring Forth.
ج; Jim; throw-stick. Walk / Carry.
ح; Ha; wall. Separate / Protect.
خ; Kha; dotted Ha. Penetrate the Boundary.
د; Dal; door. Door / Threshold.
ذ; Dhal; dotted Dal. Indicate / Point Through.
ر; Ra; head. Head / First.
ز; Zay; weapon. Cut / Nourish.
س; Sin; prop. Support / Grasp.
ش; Shin; teeth. Press / Consume.
ص; Sad; hook. Chase / Harvest.
ض; Dad; dotted Sad. Heavy Pursuit / Press Down.
ط; Ta (emphatic); basket. Surround / Contain.
ظ; Za; dotted Ta (emphatic). Appear from Within.
ع; Ayn; eye. See / Know.
غ; Ghayn; dotted Ayn. Hidden Seeing / The Unseen.
ف; Fa; mouth. Speak / Open.
ق; Qaf; back of head. Condense / Behind.
ك; Kaf; open palm. Open / Allow.
ل; Lam; shepherd's staff. Teach / Toward.
م; Mim; water. Chaos / Mighty.
ن; Nun; sprout. Continue / Heir.
ه; Ha (soft); figure with raised arms. Behold / Breath.
و; Waw; nail. Add / Connect.
ي; Ya; hand. Work / Deed.

Read right-to-left.

Letters ا through ي inherit Phoenician pictographs directly via the shared Northwest Semitic root. The six dotted letters (ث, خ, ذ, ض, ظ, غ) are sister forms created by i'jām — 
the diacritical-dot tradition that marks one letter as a variant of another. Each sister form inherits its base letter's role and modifies it: Tha extends Ta toward manifestation, Kha extends Ha toward penetration,
Dhal extends Dal toward indication, Dad extends Sad toward heavier pursuit, Za extends emphatic Ta toward appearance-from-within, and Ghayn extends Ayn toward hidden or unseen perception.

Details about other literary systems can be found at https://keyofenglish.com/glyphs
